[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Assertions can help a programmer read the code, help a compiler compile it, or help the program detect its own defects.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] For the latter, some programs check assertions by actually evaluating the predicate as they run.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Then, if it is not in fact true – an assertion failure – the program considers itself to be broken and typically deliberately crashes or throws an assertion failure exception.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Programmers can use assertions to help specify programs and to reason about program correctness.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] For example, a precondition—an assertion placed at the beginning of a section of code—determines the set of states under which the programmer expects the code to execute.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] A postcondition—placed at the end—describes the expected state at the end of execution.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] The example above uses the notation for including assertions used by C.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] That notation cannot be used in existing mainstream programming languages.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] However, programmers can include unchecked assertions using the comment feature of their programming language.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] The braces included in the comment help distinguish this use of a comment from other uses.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Libraries may provide assertion features as well.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Several modern programming languages include checked assertions – statements that are checked at runtime or sometimes statically.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] If an assertion evaluates to false at runtime, an assertion failure results, which typically causes execution to abort.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] This draws attention to the location at which the logical inconsistency is detected and can be preferable to the behaviour that would otherwise result.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] The use of assertions helps the programmer design, develop, and reason about a program.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In languages such as Eiffel, assertions form part of the design process; other languages, such as C and Java, use them only to check assumptions at runtime.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In both cases, they can be checked for validity at runtime, but can usually also be suppressed.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Assertions can function as a form of documentation: they can describe the state the code expects to find before it runs (its preconditions), and the state the code expects to result in when it is finished running (postconditions); they can also specify invariants of a class.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Eiffel integrates such assertions into the language and automatically extracts them to document the class.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] This forms an important part of the method of design by contract.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] This approach is also useful in languages that do not explicitly support it: the advantage of using assertion statements rather than assertions in comments is that the program can check the assertions every time it runs; if the assertion no longer holds, an error can be reported.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] This prevents the code from getting out of sync with the assertions.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] For example, the following demonstrates design by contract in C++ (using C++26 contracts).
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] An assertion may be used to verify that an assumption made by the programmer during the implementation of the program remains valid when the program is executed.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In Java, `%` is the *remainder* operator (*modulo*), and in Java, if its first operand is negative, the result can also be negative (unlike the modulo used in mathematics).
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer has assumed that `total` is non-negative, so that the remainder of a division by 2 will always be 0 or 1.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] The assertion makes this assumption explicit: if `countNumberOfUsers` does return a negative value, the program may have a bug.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] A major advantage of this technique is that when an error does occur, it is detected immediately and directly, rather than later through often obscure effects.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Since an assertion failure usually reports the code location, one can often pinpoint the error without further debugging.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Assertions are also sometimes placed at points where the execution is not supposed to reach.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] For example, assertions could be placed at the `default` clause of the `switch` statement in languages such as C, C++, and Java.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Any case that the programmer does not handle intentionally will raise an error, and the program will abort rather than silently continuing in an erroneous state.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In D such an assertion is added automatically when a `switch` statement doesn't contain a `default` clause.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In Java, assertions have been a part of the language since version 1.4.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Assertion failures result in raising an `AssertionError` when the program is run with the appropriate flags, without which the assert statements are ignored.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In C, they are added on by the standard header `<assert.h>` defining `assert(*assertion*)` as a macro that signals an error in the case of failure, usually terminating the program.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In C++, both `<assert.h>` and `<cassert>` headers provide the `assert` macro.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] The danger of assertions is that they may cause side effects either by changing memory data or by changing thread timing.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Assertions should be implemented carefully, so they cause no side effects on program code.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Assertion constructs in a language allow for easy test-driven development (TDD) without the use of a third-party library.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In C#, there is no assertion macro or keyword, but instead classes `System.Diagnostics.Debug` and `System.Diagnostics.Trace` which provide `Assert()` methods.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] During the development cycle, the programmer will typically run the program with assertions enabled.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] When an assertion failure occurs, the programmer is immediately notified of the problem.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Many assertion implementations will also halt the program's execution: this is useful, since if the program continued to run after an assertion violation occurred, it might corrupt its state and make the cause of the problem more difficult to locate.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Using the information provided by the assertion failure (such as the location of the failure and perhaps a stack trace, or even the full program state if the environment supports core dumps or if the program is running in a debugger), the programmer can usually fix the problem.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Thus, assertions provide a very powerful tool in debugging.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] When a program is deployed to production, assertions are typically turned off to avoid any overhead or side effects they may have.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In some cases, assertions are completely absent from deployed code, such as in C/C++ assertions via macros.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In other cases, such as Java, assertions are present in the deployed code and can be turned on in the field for debugging.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Assertions may also be used to promise the compiler that a given edge condition is not actually reachable, thereby permitting certain optimizations that would not otherwise be possible.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In this case, disabling the assertions could actually reduce performance.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Assertions that are checked at compile time are called static assertions.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Static assertions are particularly useful in compile-time template metaprogramming, but can also be used in low-level languages like C by introducing illegal code if (and only if) the assertion fails.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] C11 and C++11 support static assertions directly through `static_assert`.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] If the `(BOOLEAN CONDITION)` part evaluates to false, then the above code will not compile because the compiler will not allow two case labels with the same constant.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int)==4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] This construct does not work at file scope (i.e., not inside a function), and so it must be wrapped inside a function.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] If the `(BOOLEAN CONDITION)` part evaluates to false, then the above code will not compile because arrays may not have a negative length.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] If, in fact, the compiler allows a negative length, then the initialization byte (the `'!'` part) should cause even such over-lenient compilers to complain.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int) == 4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Both of these methods require a method of constructing unique names.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers support a `__COUNTER__` preprocessor define that facilitates the construction of unique names, by returning monotonically increasing numbers for each compilation unit.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] D provides static assertions through the use of `static assert`.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Most languages allow assertions to be enabled or disabled globally, and sometimes independently.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Assertions are often enabled during development and disabled during final testing and on release to the customer.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Not checking assertions avoids the cost of evaluating the assertions while (assuming the assertions are free of side effects) still producing the same result under normal conditions.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Under abnormal conditions, disabling assertion checking can mean that a program that would have aborted will continue to run.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Some languages, including C, YASS, and C++, can completely remove assertions at compile time using the preprocessor.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Similarly, launching the Python interpreter with "-O" (for "optimize") as an argument will cause the Python code generator to not emit any bytecode for asserts.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Java requires an option to be passed to the run-time engine in order to *enable* assertions.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Absent the option, assertions are bypassed, but they always remain in the code unless optimised away by a JIT compiler at run-time or excluded at compile time via the programmer manually placing each assertion behind an `if (false)` clause.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Programmers can build checks into their code that are always active by bypassing or manipulating the language's normal assertion-checking mechanisms.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Assertions are distinct from routine error-handling.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Assertions document logically impossible situations and discover programming errors: if the impossible occurs, then something fundamental is clearly wrong with the program.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] This is distinct from error handling: most error conditions are possible, although some may be extremely unlikely to occur in practice.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Using assertions as a general-purpose error handling mechanism is unwise: assertions do not allow for recovery from errors; an assertion failure will normally halt the program's execution abruptly; and assertions are often disabled in production code.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Assertions also do not display a user-friendly error message.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer is aware that `malloc` will return a `NULL` pointer if memory is not allocated.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] This is possible: the operating system does not guarantee that every call to `malloc` will succeed.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] If an out-of-memory error occurs, the program will immediately abort.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Without the assertion, the program would continue running until `ptr` was dereferenced, and possibly longer, depending on the specific hardware being used.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] So long as assertions are not disabled, an immediate exit is assured.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] But if a graceful failure is desired, the program has to handle the failure.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] For example, a server may have multiple clients, or may hold resources that will not be released cleanly, or it may have uncommitted changes to write to a datastore.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In such cases, it is better to fail a single transaction than to abort abruptly.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Another error is to rely on the side effects of expressions used as arguments of an assertion.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] One should always keep in mind that assertions might not be executed at all, since their sole purpose is to verify that a condition which should always be true does, in fact, hold true.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Consequently, if the program is considered to be error-free and released, assertions may be disabled and will no longer be evaluated.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] This might look like a smart way to assign the return value of `malloc` to `ptr` and check if it is `NULL` in one step, but the `malloc` call and the assignment to `ptr` is a side effect of evaluating the expression that forms the `assert` condition.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] When the `NDEBUG` parameter is passed to the compiler, as when the program is considered to be error-free and released, the `assert()` statement is removed, so `malloc()` isn't called, rendering `ptr` uninitialised.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] This could potentially result in a segmentation fault or similar null pointer error much further down the line in program execution, causing bugs that may be sporadic and/or difficult to track down.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Programmers sometimes use a similar VERIFY(X) define to alleviate this problem.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers may issue a warning when encountering the above code.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] Furthermore, we may, at such a point, indicate the validity of these limitations.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] The assertional method for proving the correctness of programs was advocated by Alan Turing.
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In a talk "Checking a Large Routine" at Cambridge, June 24, 1949, Turing suggested: "How can one check a large routine in the sense of making sure that it's right?
[src:eiffel-language/assertion-software-development] In order that the man who checks may not have too difficult a task, the programmer should make a number of definite *assertions* which can be checked individually, and from which the correctness of the whole program easily follows".
[src:eiffel-language/bertrand-meyer] Meyer is known for his books on programming languages and object-oriented programming, as well as his contributions to the Z notation specification and design of the Eiffel programming language.
[src:eiffel-language/bertrand-meyer] Meyer is a member of Academia Europaea and the French Academy of Technologies and a Fellow of the ACM.
[src:eiffel-language/bertrand-meyer] He has received honorary doctorates from ITMO University in Saint Petersburg, Russia (2004) (returned in 2022) and the University of York, England (2015).
[src:eiffel-language/bertrand-meyer] He was the first "senior award" winner of the AITO Dahl-Nygaard award in 2005.
[src:eiffel-language/bertrand-meyer] This prize, named after the two founders of object-oriented programming, is awarded annually to a senior and a junior researcher who has made significant technical contributions to the field of OOP.
[src:eiffel-language/bertrand-meyer] He is the 2009 recipient of the IEEE Computer Society Harlan Mills award "for practical & fundamental contributions to object-oriented software engineering".
[src:eiffel-language/bertrand-meyer] He is an IFIP fellow, as part of the first group to receive this distinction in 2019, and received in 2017 the ACM SIGSOFT Software Engineering Educator Award.
[src:eiffel-language/bertrand-meyer] He was the recipient of an ERC (European Research Council) Advanced Investigator Grant (2012-2017).
[src:eiffel-language/bertrand-meyer] In 2006, Meyer received the ACM Software System Award of the for "impact on software quality" in recognition of the design of Eiffel.
[src:eiffel-language/bertrand-meyer] On 28 December 2005, an anonymous user falsely announced Meyer's death on the German Wikipedia's biography of Meyer.
[src:eiffel-language/bertrand-meyer] The hoax was reported five days later by the Heise News Ticker and the article was immediately corrected.
[src:eiffel-language/bertrand-meyer] Many major news media outlets in Germany and Switzerland picked up the story.
[src:eiffel-language/bertrand-meyer] Meyer went on to publish a positive evaluation of Wikipedia, concluding "The system succumbed to one of its potential flaws, and quickly healed itself.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] It prescribes that software designers should define formal, precise and verifiable interface specifications for software components, which extend the ordinary definition of abstract data types with preconditions, postconditions and invariants.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] These specifications are referred to as "contracts", in accordance with a conceptual metaphor with the conditions and obligations of business contracts.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] The DbC approach assumes all *client components* that invoke an operation on a *server component* will meet the preconditions specified as required for that operation.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] The term was coined by Bertrand Meyer in connection with his design of the Eiffel programming language and first described in various articles starting in 1986 and the two successive editions (1988, 1997) of his book *Object-Oriented Software Construction*.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Eiffel Software applied for trademark registration for *Design by Contract* in December 2003, and it was granted in December 2004.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] The current owner of this trademark is Eiffel Software.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Design by contract has its roots in work on formal verification, formal specification and Hoare logic.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] The central idea of DbC is a metaphor on how elements of a software system collaborate with each other on the basis of mutual *obligations* and *benefits*.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] The contract is semantically equivalent to a Hoare triple which formalises the obligations.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Many programming languages have facilities to make assertions like these.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] However, DbC considers these contracts to be so crucial to software correctness that they should be part of the design process.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] In effect, DbC advocates writing the assertions first.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Contracts can be written by code comments, enforced by a test suite, or both, even if there is no special language support for contracts.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Subclasses in an inheritance hierarchy are allowed to weaken preconditions (but not strengthen them) and strengthen postconditions and invariants (but not weaken them).
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] These rules approximate behavioural subtyping.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] All class relationships are between client classes and supplier classes.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] A client class is obliged to make calls to supplier features where the resulting state of the supplier is not violated by the client call.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Subsequently, the supplier is obliged to provide a return state and data that does not violate the state requirements of the client.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] For instance, a supplier data buffer may require that data is present in the buffer when a delete feature is called.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Subsequently, the supplier guarantees to the client that when a delete feature finishes its work, the data item will, indeed, be deleted from the buffer.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Other design contracts are concepts of class invariant.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] The class invariant guarantees (for the local class) that the state of the class will be maintained within specified tolerances at the end of each feature execution.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] When using contracts, a supplier will verify that the contract conditions are satisfied—a practice known as offensive programming—the general idea being that code should "fail hard", with contract verification being the safety net.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] DbC's "fail hard" property simplifies the debugging of contract behavior, as the intended behaviour of each method is clearly specified.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] This approach differs substantially from that of defensive programming, where the supplier is responsible for figuring out what to do when a precondition is broken.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] More often than not, the supplier throws an exception to inform the client that the precondition has been broken, and in both cases—DbC and defensive programming alike—the client must figure out how to respond to that.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] In such cases, DbC makes the supplier's job easier.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Design by contract can also facilitate code reuse, since the contract for each piece of code is fully documented.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] The contracts for a module can be regarded as a form of software documentation for the behavior of that module.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Contract conditions should never be violated during execution of a bug-free program.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Contracts are therefore typically only checked in debug mode during software development.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Later at release, the contract checks are disabled to maximize performance.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] In many programming languages, contracts are implemented with assert.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Asserts are by default compiled away in release mode in C/C++, and similarly deactivated in C# and Java.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Launching the Python interpreter with "-O" (for "optimize") as an argument will likewise cause the Python code generator to not emit any bytecode for asserts.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] This effectively eliminates the run-time costs of asserts in production code—irrespective of the number and computational expense of asserts used in development—as no such instructions will be included in production by the compiler.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Design by contract does not replace regular testing strategies, such as unit testing, integration testing and system testing.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Rather, it complements external testing with internal self-tests that can be activated both for isolated tests and in production code during a test-phase.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] The advantage of internal self-tests is that they can detect errors before they manifest themselves as invalid results observed by the client.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] This leads to earlier and more specific error detection.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] The use of assertions can be considered to be a form of test oracle, a way of testing the design by contract implementation.
[src:eiffel-language/design-by-contract] Further, the standard method combination in the Common Lisp Object System has the method qualifiers `:before`, `:after` and `:around` that allow writing contracts as auxiliary methods, among other uses.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The design of the language is closely connected with the Eiffel programming method.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Both are based on a set of principles, including design by contract, command–query separation, the uniform-access principle, the single-choice principle, the open–closed principle, and option–operand separation.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Many concepts initially introduced by Eiffel were later added into Java, C#, and other languages.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] New language design ideas, particularly through the Ecma/ISO standardization process, continue to be incorporated into the Eiffel language.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel emphasizes declarative statements over procedural code and attempts to eliminate the need for bookkeeping instructions.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel shuns coding tricks or techniques intended as program optimization hints to a compiler.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The goals are to make the code more readable, and to facilitate concentrating on the important aspects of a program without getting bogged down in implementation details.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel's simplicity is intended to promote simple, extensible, reusable, and reliable answers to computing problems.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Compilers for computer programs written in Eiffel provide extensive optimizing techniques, such as automatic inline expansion (inlining), that eliminate part of the optimizing burden.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel was originally developed by Eiffel Software, a company founded by Bertrand Meyer.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] *Object-Oriented Software Construction* contains a detailed treatment of the concepts and theory of the object technology that led to Eiffel's design.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The design goal behind the Eiffel language, libraries, and programming methods is to enable programmers to create reliable, reusable software modules.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel supports multiple inheritance, genericity, polymorphism, encapsulation, type-safe conversions, and parameter covariance.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel's most important contribution to software engineering is design by contract (DbC), in which assertions, preconditions, postconditions, and class invariants are employed to help ensure program correctness without sacrificing efficiency.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel's design is based on object-oriented programming theory, with only minor influence of other programming paradigms or concern for support of legacy code.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel formally supports abstract data types.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Under Eiffel's design, a software text should be able to reproduce its design documentation from the text itself, using a formalized implementation of the "Abstract Data Type".
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] EiffelStudio is an integrated development environment available under either an open source or a commercial license.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] It offers an object-oriented environment for software engineering, compiling to either C or .NET.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] EiffelEnvision is a plug-in for Microsoft Visual Studio that allows users to edit, compile, and debug Eiffel projects from within the Microsoft Visual Studio IDE.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Five other open source implementations are available: "The Eiffel Compiler" tecomp; Gobo Eiffel; SmartEiffel, the GNU implementation, based on an older version of the language; LibertyEiffel, based on the SmartEiffel compiler; and Visual Eiffel.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Several other programming languages incorporate elements first introduced in Eiffel.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Sather, for example, was originally based on Eiffel but has since diverged, and now includes several functional programming features.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The interactive-teaching language Blue, forerunner of BlueJ, is also Eiffel-based.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The Apple Media Tool includes an Eiffel-based Apple Media Language.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The Eiffel language definition is an international standard of the ISO.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The standard was developed by ECMA International, which first approved the standard on 21 June 2005 as Standard ECMA-367, Eiffel: Analysis, Design and Programming Language.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] In June 2006, ECMA and ISO adopted the second version.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] In November 2006, ISO first published that version.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The standard can be found and used free of charge on the ECMA site.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The ISO version is identical in all respects except formatting.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The SmartEiffel team has turned away from this standard to create its own version of the language, which they believe to be closer to the original style of Eiffel.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Object Tools has not disclosed whether future versions of its Eiffel compiler will comply with the standard.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] LibertyEiffel implements a dialect somewhere in between the SmartEiffel language and the standard.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The current version of the standard from June 2006 contains some inconsistencies (e.g. covariant redefinitions).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The ECMA committee has not yet announced any timeline and direction on how to resolve the inconsistencies.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] An Eiffel "system" or "program" is a collection of *classes*.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Above the level of classes, Eiffel defines *cluster*, which is essentially a group of classes, and possibly of *subclusters* (nested clusters).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Clusters are not a syntactic language construct, but rather a standard organizational convention.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Typically an Eiffel program will be organized with each class in a separate file, and each cluster in a directory containing class files.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] In this organization, subclusters are subdirectories.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] For example, under standard organizational and casing conventions, `x.e` might be the name of a file that defines a class called X.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] A class contains *features*, which are similar to "routines", "members", "attributes" or "methods" in other object-oriented programming languages.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] A class also defines its invariants, and contains other properties, such as a "notes" section for documentation and metadata.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel's standard data types, such as `INTEGER`, `STRING` and `ARRAY`, are all themselves classes.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Every system must have a class designated as "root", with one of its creation procedures designated as "root procedure".
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Executing a system consists of creating an instance of the root class and executing its root procedure.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Generally, doing so creates new objects, calls new features, and so on.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel has five basic executable instructions: assignment, object creation, routine call, condition, and iteration.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel's control structures are strict in enforcing structured programming: every block has exactly one entry and exactly one exit.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] To put it in the language of other object-oriented programming languages, all Eiffel attributes are "protected", and "setters" are needed for client objects to modify values.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] An upshot of this is that "setters" can and normally do, implement the invariants for which Eiffel provides syntax.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] While a slight bow to the overall developer community to allow something looking like direct access (e.g. thereby breaking the Information Hiding Principle), the practice is dangerous as it hides or obfuscates the reality of a "setter" being used.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] In practice, it is better to redirect the call to a setter rather than implying a direct access to a feature like `some_attribute` as in the example code above.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Unlike other languages, having notions of "public", "protected", "private" and so on, Eiffel uses an exporting technology to more precisely control the scoping between client and supplier classes.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Feature visibility is checked statically at compile-time.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] For example, (below), the `{NONE}` is similar to "protected" in other languages.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Scope applied this way to a "feature set" (e.g. everything below the 'feature' keyword to either the next feature set keyword or the end of the class) can be changed in descendant classes using the "export" keyword.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Alternatively, the lack of a `{x}` export declaration implies `{ANY}` and is similar to the "public" scoping of other languages.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Here, the compiler will allow only the classes listed between the curly braces to access the features within the feature group (e.g.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] DECIMAL, DCM_MA_DECIMAL_PARSER, DCM_MA_DECIMAL_HANDLER).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] A programming language's look and feel is often conveyed using a "Hello, world!" program.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] This program contains the class `HELLO_WORLD`.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The constructor (create routine) for the class, named `make`, invokes the `print` system library routine to write a Hello, world! message to the output.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The concept of Design by Contract is central to Eiffel.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The contracts assert what must be true before a routine is executed (precondition) and what must hold to be true after the routine finishes (post-condition).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Class Invariant contracts define what assertions must hold true both before and after any feature of a class is accessed (both routines and attributes).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Moreover, contracts codify into executable code developer and designers assumptions about the operating environment of the features of a class or the class as a whole by means of the invariant.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The Eiffel compiler is designed to include the feature and class contracts in various levels.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] EiffelStudio, for example, executes all feature and class contracts during execution in the "Workbench mode." When an executable is created, the compiler is instructed by way of the project settings file (e.g.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] ECF file) to either include or exclude any set of contracts.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Thus, an executable file can be compiled to either include or exclude any level of contract, thereby bringing along continuous levels of unit and integration testing.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Moreover, contracts can be continually and methodically exercised by way of the Auto-Test feature found in EiffelStudio.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] In addition, the language supports a "check instruction" (a kind of "assert"), loop invariants, and loop variants (which guarantee loop termination).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Void-safe ability, like static typing, is another facility for improving software quality.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Void-safe software is protected from runtime errors caused by calls to void references, and therefore will be more reliable than software in which calls to void targets can occur.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The analogy to static typing is a useful one.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Void-safe ability can be seen as an extension to the type system, or a step beyond static typing, because the mechanism for ensuring void safety is integrated into the type system.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The guard against void target calls can be seen by way of the notion of attachment and (by extension) detachment (e.g. detachable keyword).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The code example above shows how the compiler can statically address the reliability of whether `some_attribute` will be attached or detached at the point it is used.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Notably, the `attached` keyword allows for an "attachment local" (e.g.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] `l_attribute`), which is scoped to only the block of code enclosed by the if-statement construct.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Thus, within this small block of code, the local variable (e.g.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] `l_attribute`) can be statically guaranteed to be non-void (i.e. void safe).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The primary characteristic of a class is that it defines a set of features: as a class represents a set of run-time objects, or "instances", a feature is an operation on these objects.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] There are two kinds of features: queries and commands.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] A query provides information about an instance.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The command-query distinction is important to the Eiffel method.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel does not allow argument overloading.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Each feature name within a class always maps to a specific feature within the class.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] One name, within one class, means one thing.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] This design choice helps the readability of classes, by avoiding a cause of ambiguity about which routine will be invoked by a call.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] It also simplifies the language mechanism; in particular, this is what makes Eiffel's multiple inheritance mechanism possible.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Names can, of course, be reused in different classes.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] For example, the feature plus (along with its infix alias "+") is defined in several classes: INTEGER, REAL, STRING, etc.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] A generic class is a class that varies by type (e.g.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] `LIST [PHONE]`, a list of phone numbers; `ACCOUNT [G->ACCOUNT_TYPE]`, allowing for `ACCOUNT [SAVINGS]` and `ACCOUNT [CHECKING]`, etc.).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Classes can be generic, to express that they are parameterized by types.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] G is known as a "formal generic parameter".
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The `LIST [INTEGER]` and `LIST [WORD]` are "generic derivations" of this class.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] `INTEGER` and `WORD` are the "actual generic parameters" in these generic derivations.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] It is also possible to have 'constrained' formal parameters, for which the actual parameter must inherit from a given class, the "constraint".
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] a derivation `HASH_TABLE [INTEGER, STRING]` is valid only if `STRING` inherits from `HASHABLE` (as it indeed does in typical Eiffel libraries).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Within the class, having `KEY` constrained by `HASHABLE` means that for `x: KEY` it is possible to apply to `x` all the features of `HASHABLE`, as in `x.hash_code`.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The class may redefine (override) some or all of the inherited features.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] See for a complete discussion of Eiffel inheritance.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Classes may be defined with `deferred class` rather than with `class` to indicate that the class may not be directly instantiated.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Non-instantiatable classes are called abstract classes in some other object-oriented programming languages.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] In Eiffel parlance, only an "effective" class can be instantiated (it may be a descendant of a deferred class).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] A feature can also be deferred by using the `deferred` keyword in place of a `do` clause.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] If a class has any deferred features it must be declared as deferred; however, a class with no deferred features may nonetheless itself be deferred.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Deferred classes play some of the same role as interfaces in languages such as Java, though many object-oriented programming theorists believe interfaces are themselves largely an answer to Java's lack of multiple inheritance (which Eiffel has).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] A class that inherits from one or more others gets all its features, by default under their original names.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] It may, however, change their names through `rename` clauses.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] This is required in the case of multiple inheritance if there are name clashes between inherited features; without renaming, the resulting class would violate the no-overloading principle noted above and hence would be invalid.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Tuples types may be viewed as a simple form of class, providing only attributes and the corresponding "setter" procedure.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] and could be used to describe a simple notion of birth record if a class is not needed.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Components of such a tuple can be accessed as if the tuple tags were attributes of a class, for example if `t` has been assigned the above tuple then `t.weight` has value 3.5.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The tuple tags are optional, so that it is also possible to write a tuple type as `TUPLE [STRING, REAL, DATE]`.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] `TUPLE [A, B, C]` is that it describes sequences of *at least* three elements, the first three being of types `A`, `B`, `C` respectively.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] As a result, `TUPLE [A, B, C]` conforms to (may be assigned to) `TUPLE [A, B]`, to `TUPLE [A]` and to `TUPLE` (without parameters), the topmost tuple type to which all tuple types conform.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel's "agent" mechanism wraps operations into objects.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] This mechanism can be used for iteration, event-driven programming, and other contexts in which it is useful to pass operations around the program structure.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Other programming languages, especially ones that emphasize functional programming, allow a similar pattern using continuations, closures, or generators; Eiffel's agents emphasize the language's object-oriented paradigm, and use a syntax and semantics similar to code blocks in Smalltalk and Ruby.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] In these examples, `my_action` and `my_condition` are routines.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Prefixing them with `agent` yields an object that represents the corresponding routine with all its properties, in particular the ability to be called with the appropriate arguments.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] will call the original routine with the argument `x`, as if we had directly called the original routine: `my_action (x)`.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Arguments to `call` are passed as a tuple, here `[x]`.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] It is possible to keep some arguments to an agent **open** and make others **closed**.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The open arguments are passed as arguments to `call`: they are provided at the time of *agent use*.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The closed arguments are provided at the time of agent *definition*.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] iterates `action2 (x, y)` for successive values of `x`, where the second argument remains set to `y`.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The question mark `?` indicates an open argument; `y` is a closed argument of the agent.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Note that the basic syntax `agent f` is a shorthand for `agent f (?, ?, ...)` with all arguments open.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] It is also possible to make the *target* of an agent open through the notation `{T}?` where `T` is the type of the target.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The distinction between open and closed operands (operands = arguments + target) corresponds to the distinction between bound and free variables in lambda calculus.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] An agent expression such as `action2 (?, y)` with some operands closed and some open corresponds to a version of the original operation *curried* on the closed operands.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The inline agent passed here can have all the trappings of a normal routine, including precondition, postcondition, rescue clause (not used here), and a full signature.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] This avoids defining routines when all that's needed is a computation to be wrapped in an agent.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The current agent mechanism leaves a possibility of run-time type error (if a routine with *n* arguments is passed to an agent expecting *m* arguments with *m* < *n*).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] This can be avoided by a run-time check through the precondition `valid_arguments` of `call`.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Several proposals for a purely static correction of this problem are available, including a language change proposal by Ribet et al.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] A routine's result can be cached using the `once` keyword in place of `do`.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Non-first calls to a routine require no additional computation or resource allocation, but simply return a previously computed result.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] A common pattern for "once functions" is to provide shared objects; the first call will create the object, subsequent ones will return the reference to that object.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The returned object—`Result` in the example—can itself be mutable, but its reference remains the same.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Often "once routines" perform a required initialization: multiple calls to a library can include a call to the initialization procedure, but only the first such call will perform the required actions.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Using this pattern initialization can be decentralized, avoiding the need for a special initialization module.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] "Once routines" are similar in purpose and effect to the singleton pattern in many programming languages, and to the Borg pattern used in Python.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] By default, a "once routine" is called *once per thread*.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The semantics can be adjusted to *once per process* or *once per object* by qualifying it with a "once key", e.g.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel provides a mechanism to allow conversions between various types.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The mechanisms coexists with inheritance and complements it.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] (Conversion principle) A type may not both conform and convert to another.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] For example, `NEWSPAPER` may conform to `PUBLICATION`, but `INTEGER` converts to `REAL` (and does not inherit from it).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The conversion mechanism simply generalizes the ad hoc conversion rules (such as indeed between `INTEGER` and `REAL`) that exist in most programming languages, making them applicable to any type as long as the above principle is observed.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] To make the first form possible as a synonym for the second, it suffices to list the creation procedure (constructor) `make_from_date` in a `convert` clause at the beginning of the class.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Exception handling in Eiffel is based on the principles of design by contract.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] For example, an exception occurs when a routine's caller fails to satisfy a precondition, or when a routine cannot ensure a promised postcondition.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] In Eiffel, exception handling is not used for control flow or to correct data-input mistakes.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] An Eiffel exception handler is defined using the rescue keyword.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Within the rescue section, the retry keyword executes the routine again.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] This example is arguably flawed for anything but the simplest programs, however, because connection failure is to be expected.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] For most programs a routine name like attempt_connecting_to_server would be better, and the postcondition would not promise a connection, leaving it up to the caller to take appropriate steps if the connection was not opened.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] A number of networking and threading libraries are available, such as EiffelNet and EiffelThreads.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] A concurrency model for Eiffel, based on the concepts of design by contract, is SCOOP, or *Simple Concurrent Object-Oriented Programming*, not yet part of the official language definition but available in EiffelStudio.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] CAMEO is an (unimplemented) variation of SCOOP for Eiffel.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Concurrency also interacts with exceptions.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Asynchronous exceptions can be troublesome (where a routine raises an exception after its caller has itself finished).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel's view of computation is completely object-oriented in the sense that every operation is relative to an object, the "target".
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] with target `a`, feature `plus` and argument `b`.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Of course, the former is the conventional syntax and usually preferred.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The range of operators that can be used as "alias" is quite broad; they include predefined operators such as "+" but also "free operators" made of non-alphanumeric symbols.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] This makes it possible to design special infix and prefix notations, for example in mathematics and physics applications.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Every class may in addition have *one* function aliased to "[]", the "bracket" operator, allowing the notation `a [i, ...]` as a synonym for `a.f (i, ...)` where `f` is the chosen function.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] This is particularly useful for container structures such as arrays, hash tables, lists etc.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] "Assigner commands" are a companion mechanism designed in the same spirit of allowing well-established, convenient notation reinterpreted in the framework of object-oriented programming.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Assigner commands allow assignment-like syntax to call "setter" procedures.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] An assignment proper can never be of the form `a.x := v` as this violates information hiding; you have to go for a setter command (procedure).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] This declares `put` as the assigner command associated with `item` and, combined with the bracket alias, makes ☝︎3 legal and equivalent to ☝︎2.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] (It could also be written, without taking advantage of the bracket, as `phone_book.item ("JILL SMITH") := New_person`.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The tokens `make`, `maKe` and `MAKE` all denote the same identifier.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Comments are introduced by `--` (two consecutive dashes) and extend to the end of the line.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The semicolon, as instruction separator, is optional.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Most of the time the semicolon is just omitted, except to separate multiple instructions on a line.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] This results in less clutter on the program page.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] There is no nesting of feature and class declarations.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] As a result, the structure of an Eiffel class is simple: some class-level clauses (inheritance, invariant) and a succession of feature declarations, all at the same level.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] In contrast to most curly bracket programming languages, Eiffel makes a clear distinction between expressions and instructions.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] This is in line with the Command-Query Separation principle of the Eiffel method.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Much of the documentation of Eiffel uses distinctive style conventions, designed to enforce a consistent look-and-feel.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Some of these conventions apply to the code format itself, and others to the standard typographic rendering of Eiffel code in formats and publications where these conventions are possible.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] While the language is case-insensitive, the style standards prescribe the use of all-capitals for class names (`LIST`), all-lower-case for feature names (`make`), and initial capitals for constants (`Avogadro`).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The recommended style also suggests underscore to separate components of a multi-word identifier, as in `average_temperature`.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel is a purely object-oriented language but provides an open architecture for interfacing with "external" software in any other programming language.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] It is possible for example to program machine- and operating-system level operations in C.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] Eiffel provides a straightforward interface to C routines, including support for "inline C" (writing the body of an Eiffel routine in C, typically for short machine-level operations).
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] There is no direct connection between Eiffel and C.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] However, many Eiffel compilers (Visual Eiffel is one exception) emit C source code as an intermediate language, to submit to a C compiler, for optimizing or porting.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] As such, they are examples of transcompilers.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The Eiffel Compiler tecomp can execute Eiffel code directly (like an interpreter) without going via an intermediate C code or emit C code which will be passed to a C compiler to obtain optimized native code.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] On .NET, the EiffelStudio compiler directly generates Common Intermediate Language (CIL) code.
[src:eiffel-language/eiffel-programming-language] The SmartEiffel compiler can also emit Java bytecode.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In object-oriented programming, **inheritance** is the mechanism of basing an object or class upon another object (prototype-based inheritance) or class (class-based inheritance), retaining similar implementation.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] It is also defined as deriving new classes (sub classes) from existing ones such as super class or base class and then forming them into a hierarchy of classes.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In most class-based object-oriented languages like C++, an object created through inheritance, a "child object", acquires all the properties and behaviors of the "parent object", with the exception of: constructors, destructors, overloaded operators and friend functions of the base class.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Inheritance allows programmers to create classes that are built upon existing classes, to specify a new implementation while maintaining the same behaviors (realizing an interface), to reuse code and to independently extend original software via public classes and interfaces.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The relationships of objects or classes through inheritance give rise to a directed acyclic graph.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] An inherited class is called a **subclass** of its parent class or super class.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Class-modifying inheritance patterns can be pre-defined according to simple network interface parameters such that inter-language compatibility is preserved.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Inheritance should not be confused with subtyping.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In some languages, generally statically-typed class-based OO languages, like C++, C#, Java, and Scala, inheritance and subtyping agree, whereas in others they differ.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In general, subtyping establishes an *is-a* relationship, whereas inheritance only reuses implementation and establishes a syntactic relationship, not necessarily a semantic relationship (inheritance does not ensure behavioral subtyping).
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] To distinguish these concepts, subtyping is sometimes referred to as *interface inheritance* (without acknowledging that the specialization of type variables also induces a subtyping relation), whereas inheritance as defined here is known as *implementation inheritance* or *code inheritance*.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Still, inheritance is a commonly used mechanism for establishing subtype relationships.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Inheritance is contrasted with object composition, where one object *contains* another object (or objects of one class contain objects of another class); see composition over inheritance.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In contrast to subtyping’s *is-a* relationship, composition implements a *has-a* relationship.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Mathematically speaking, inheritance in any system of classes induces a strict partial order on the set of classes in that system.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In 1966, Tony Hoare presented some remarks on records, and in particular, the idea of record subclasses, record types with common properties but discriminated by a variant tag and having fields private to the variant.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Influenced by this, in 1967 Ole-Johan Dahl and Kristen Nygaard presented a design that allowed specifying objects that belonged to different classes but had common properties.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The common properties were collected in a superclass, and each superclass could itself potentially have a superclass.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The values of a subclass were thus compound objects, consisting of some number of prefix parts belonging to various superclasses, plus a main part belonging to the subclass.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] These parts were all concatenated together.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The attributes of a compound object would be accessible by dot notation.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] This idea was first adopted in the Simula 67 programming language.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The idea then spread to Smalltalk, C++, Java, Python, and many other languages.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] There are various types of inheritance, based on paradigm and specific language.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] where subclasses inherit the features of one superclass.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] A class acquires the properties of another class.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] where one class can have more than one superclass and inherit features from all parent classes.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] where a subclass is inherited from another subclass.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] It is not uncommon that a class is derived from another derived class as shown in the figure "Multilevel inheritance".
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] This process can be extended to any number of levels.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] This is where one class serves as a superclass (base class) for more than one sub class.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] For example, a parent class, A, can have two subclasses B and C.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Both B and C's parent class is A, but B and C are two separate subclasses.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Hybrid inheritance is when a mix of two or more of the above types of inheritance occurs.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] An example of this is when a class A has a subclass B which has two subclasses, C and D.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] This is a mixture of both multilevel inheritance and hierarchal inheritance.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The colon indicates that the subclass inherits from the superclass.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The visibility modifier is optional and, if present, may be either *private* or *public*.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The default visibility (if there is no modifier present) is *private*.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Visibility specifies whether the features of the base class are *privately derived* or *publicly derived*.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Some languages also support the inheritance of other constructs.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] For example, in Eiffel, contracts that define the specification of a class are also inherited by heirs.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The superclass establishes a common interface and foundational functionality, which specialized subclasses can inherit, modify, and supplement.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The software inherited by a subclass is considered reused in the subclass.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] A reference to an instance of a class may actually be referring to one of its subclasses.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The actual class of the object being referenced is impossible to predict at compile-time.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] A uniform interface is used to invoke the member functions of objects of a number of different classes.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Subclasses may replace superclass functions with entirely new functions that must share the same method signature.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In some languages a class may be declared as non-subclassable by adding certain class modifiers to the class declaration.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Examples include the `final` keyword in Java and C++11 onwards or the `sealed` keyword in C#.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Such modifiers are added to the class declaration before the `class` keyword and the class identifier declaration.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Such non-subclassable classes restrict reusability, particularly when developers only have access to precompiled binaries and not source code.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Just as classes may be non-subclassable, method declarations may contain method modifiers that prevent the method from being overridden (i.e. replaced with a new function with the same name and type signature in a subclass).
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] A private method is un-overridable simply because it is not accessible by classes other than the class it is a member function of (this is not true for C++, though).
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] A `final` method in Java, a `sealed` method in C# or a `frozen` feature in Eiffel cannot be overridden.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] If a superclass method is a virtual method, then invocations of the superclass method will be dynamically dispatched.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Some languages require that method be specifically declared as virtual (e.g.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] C++), and in others, all methods are virtual (e.g.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] An invocation of a non-virtual method will always be statically dispatched (i.e. the address of the function call is determined at compile-time).
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Static dispatch is faster than dynamic dispatch and allows optimizations such as inline expansion.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The following table shows which variables and functions get inherited dependent on the visibility given when deriving the class, using the terminology established by C++.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Inheritance is used to co-relate two or more classes to each other.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Many object-oriented programming languages permit a class or object to replace the implementation of an aspect—typically a behavior—that it has inherited.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Overriding introduces a complication: which version of the behavior does an instance of the inherited class use—the one that is part of its own class, or the one from the parent (base) class?
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The answer varies between programming languages, and some languages provide the ability to indicate that a particular behavior is not to be overridden and should behave as defined by the base class.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] For instance, in C#, the base method or property can only be overridden in a subclass if it is marked with the virtual, abstract, or override modifier, while in programming languages such as Java, different methods can be called to override other methods.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] An alternative to overriding is hiding the inherited code.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Implementation inheritance is the mechanism whereby a subclass re-uses code in a base class.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] By default the subclass retains all of the operations of the base class, but the subclass may override some or all operations, replacing the base-class implementation with its own.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In the following example, subclasses `SquareSumComputer` and `CubeSumComputer` override the `transform()` method of the base class `SumComputer`.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The base class comprises operations to compute the sum of the squares between two integers.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The subclass re-uses all of the functionality of the base class with the exception of the operation that transforms a number into its square, replacing it with an operation that transforms a number into its square and cube respectively.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The subclasses therefore compute the sum of the squares/cubes between two integers.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In most quarters, class inheritance for the sole purpose of code reuse has fallen out of favor.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The primary concern is that implementation inheritance does not provide any assurance of polymorphic substitutability—an instance of the reusing class cannot necessarily be substituted for an instance of the inherited class.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] An alternative technique, explicit delegation, requires more programming effort, but avoids the substitutability issue.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In C++ private inheritance can be used as a form of *implementation inheritance* without substitutability.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Whereas public inheritance represents an "is-a" relationship and delegation represents a "has-a" relationship, private (and protected) inheritance can be thought of as an "is implemented in terms of" relationship.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Another frequent use of inheritance is to guarantee that classes maintain a certain common interface; that is, they implement the same methods.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The parent class can be a combination of implemented operations and operations that are to be implemented in the child classes.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Often, there is no interface change between the supertype and subtype- the child implements the behavior described instead of its parent class.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Inheritance is similar to but distinct from subtyping.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Subtyping enables a given type to be substituted for another type or abstraction and is said to establish an *is-a* relationship between the subtype and some existing abstraction, either implicitly or explicitly, depending on language support.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The relationship can be expressed explicitly via inheritance in languages that support inheritance as a subtyping mechanism.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] For example, the following C++ code establishes an explicit inheritance relationship between classes *B* and *A*, where *B* is both a subclass and a subtype of *A* and can be used as an *A* wherever a *B* is specified (via a reference, a pointer or the object itself).
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In programming languages that do not support inheritance as a subtyping mechanism, the relationship between a base class and a derived class is only a relationship between implementations (a mechanism for code reuse), as compared to a relationship between types.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Inheritance, even in programming languages that support inheritance as a subtyping mechanism, does not necessarily entail behavioral subtyping.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] It is entirely possible to derive a class whose object will behave incorrectly when used in a context where the parent class is expected; see the Liskov substitution principle.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] (Compare connotation/denotation.) In some OOP languages, the notions of code reuse and subtyping coincide because the only way to declare a subtype is to define a new class that inherits the implementation of another.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Using inheritance extensively in designing a program imposes certain constraints.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] For example, consider a class `Person` that contains a person's name, date of birth, address and phone number.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] We can define a subclass of Person called `Student` that contains the person's grade point average and classes taken, and another subclass of Person called Employee that contains the person's job-title, employer, and salary.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The composite reuse principle is an alternative to inheritance.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] This technique supports polymorphism and code reuse by separating behaviors from the primary class hierarchy and including specific behavior classes as required in any business domain class.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] This approach avoids the static nature of a class hierarchy by allowing behavior modifications at run time and allows one class to implement behaviors buffet-style, instead of being restricted to the behaviors of its ancestor classes.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Implementation inheritance has been controversial among programmers and theoreticians of object-oriented programming since at least the 1990s.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Among the critics are the authors of *Design Patterns*, who advocate instead for interface inheritance, and favor composition over inheritance.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] For example, the decorator pattern (as mentioned above) has been proposed to overcome the static nature of inheritance between classes.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] As a more fundamental solution to the same problem, role-oriented programming introduces a distinct relationship, *played-by*, combining properties of inheritance and composition into a new concept.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] According to Allen Holub, the main problem with implementation inheritance is that it introduces unnecessary coupling in the form of the "fragile base class problem": modifications to the base class implementation can cause inadvertent behavioral changes in subclasses.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Using interfaces avoids this problem because no implementation is shared, only the API.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Another way of stating this is that "inheritance breaks encapsulation".
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The problem surfaces clearly in open object-oriented systems such as frameworks, where client code is expected to inherit from system-supplied classes and then substituted for the system's classes in its algorithms.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Reportedly, Java inventor James Gosling has spoken against implementation inheritance, stating that he would not include it if he were to redesign Java.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Language designs that decouple inheritance from subtyping (interface inheritance) appeared as early as 1990; a modern example of this is the Go programming language.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Complex inheritance, or inheritance used within an insufficiently mature design, may lead to the yo-yo problem.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] When inheritance was used as a primary approach to structure programs in the late 1990s, developers tended to break code into more layers of inheritance as the system functionality grew.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] If a development team combined multiple layers of inheritance with the single responsibility principle, this resulted in many very thin layers of code, with many layers consisting of only 1 or 2 lines of actual code.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Too many layers make debugging a significant challenge, as it becomes hard to determine which layer needs to be debugged.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Another issue with inheritance is that subclasses must be defined in code, which means that program users cannot add new subclasses at runtime.
[src:eiffel-language/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Other design patterns (such as Entity–component–system) allow program users to define variations of an entity at runtime.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Notable languages with OOP support include Ada, ActionScript, C++, Common Lisp, C#, Dart, Eiffel, Fortran 2003, Haxe, Java, JavaScript, Kotlin, Logo, MATLAB, Objective-C, Object Pascal, Perl, PHP, Python, R, Raku, Ruby, Scala, SIMSCRIPT, Simula, Smalltalk, Swift, Vala and Visual Basic (.NET).
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] The idea of "objects" in programming began with the artificial intelligence group at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in the late 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Here, "object" referred to LISP atoms with identified properties (attributes).
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Another early example was Sketchpad created by Ivan Sutherland at MIT in 1960–1961.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In the glossary of his technical report, Sutherland defined terms like "object" and "instance" (with the class concept covered by "master" or "definition"), albeit specialized to graphical interaction.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Later, in 1968, AED-0, MIT's version of the ALGOL programming language, connected data structures ("plexes") and procedures, prefiguring what were later termed "messages", "methods", and "member functions".
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Topics such as data abstraction and modular programming were common points of discussion at this time.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Meanwhile, in Norway, Simula was developed during the years 1961–1967.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Simula introduced essential object-oriented ideas, such as classes, inheritance, and dynamic binding.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Simula was used mainly by researchers involved with physical modelling, like the movement of ships and their content through cargo ports.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Simula is generally accepted as being the first language with the primary features and framework of an object-oriented language.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Influenced by both MIT and Simula, Alan Kay began developing his own ideas in November 1966.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] He would go on to create Smalltalk, an influential OOP language.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] By 1967, Kay was already using the term "object-oriented programming" in conversation.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Although sometimes called the "father" of OOP, Kay has said his ideas differ from how OOP is commonly understood, and has implied that the computer science establishment did not adopt his notion.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] A 1976 MIT memo co-authored by Barbara Liskov lists Simula 67, CLU, and Alphard as object-oriented languages, but does not mention Smalltalk.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In the 1970s, the first version of the Smalltalk programming language was developed at Xerox PARC by Alan Kay, Dan Ingalls and Adele Goldberg.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Smalltalk-72 was notable for use of objects at the language level and its graphical development environment.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Smalltalk was a fully dynamic system, allowing users to create and modify classes as they worked.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Much of the theory of OOP was developed in the context of Smalltalk, for example multiple inheritance.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In the late 1970s and 1980s, OOP rose to prominence.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] The Flavors object-oriented Lisp was developed starting 1979, introducing multiple inheritance and mixins.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In August 1981, Byte Magazine highlighted Smalltalk and OOP, introducing these ideas to a wide audience.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] LOOPS, the object system for Interlisp-D, was influenced by Smalltalk and Flavors, and a paper about it was published in 1982.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In 1986, the first *Conference on Object-Oriented Programming, Systems, Languages, and Applications* (OOPSLA) was attended by 1,000 people.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] This conference marked the start of efforts to consolidate Lisp object systems, eventually resulting in the Common Lisp Object System.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In the 1980s, there were a few attempts to design processor architectures that included hardware support for objects in memory, but these were not successful.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Examples include the Intel iAPX 432 and the Linn Smart Rekursiv.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In the mid-1980s, new object-oriented languages like Objective-C, C++, and the Eiffel language emerged.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Objective-C was developed by Brad Cox, who had used Smalltalk at ITT Inc.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Bjarne Stroustrup created C++ based on his experience using Simula for his PhD thesis.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Bertrand Meyer produced the first design of the Eiffel language in 1985, which focused on software quality using a design by contract approach.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In the 1990s, OOP became the main way of programming, especially as more languages supported it.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] These included Visual FoxPro 3.0, C++, and Delphi.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] OOP became even more popular with the rise of graphical user interfaces, which used objects for buttons, menus and other elements.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] One well-known example is Apple's Cocoa framework, used on macOS and written in Objective-C.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] OOP toolkits also enhanced the popularity of event-driven programming.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] At ETH Zürich, Niklaus Wirth and his colleagues created new approaches to OOP.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Modula-2 (1978) and Oberon (1987), included a distinctive approach to object orientation, classes, and type checking across module boundaries.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance is not obvious in Wirth's design since his nomenclature looks in the opposite direction: It is called type extension and the viewpoint is from the parent down to the inheritor.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Many programming languages that were initially developed before OOP was popular have been augmented with object-oriented features, including Ada, BASIC, Fortran, Pascal, and COBOL.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] The OOP features provided by languages vary.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Below are some common features of OOP languages.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Comparing OOP with other styles, like relational programming, is difficult because there isn't a clear, agreed-upon definition of OOP.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Some programming languages, like Java, provide information hiding via visibility key words (`private` and `public`).
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Some languages like Python don't provide a visibility feature, but developers might follow a convention such as starting a private member name with an underscore.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Intermediate levels of access also exist, such as Java's `protected` keyword, (which allows access from the same class and its subclasses, but not objects of a different class), and the `internal` keyword in C#, Swift, and Kotlin, which restricts access to files within the same module.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Supporters of information hiding and data abstraction say it makes code easier to reuse and intuitively represents real-world situations.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] However, others argue that OOP does not enhance readability or modularity.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Raymond has written that OOP languages tend to encourage thickly layered programs that destroy transparency.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Raymond compares this unfavourably to the approach taken with Unix and the C language.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] SOLID includes the open/closed principle, which says that classes and functions should be "open for extension, but closed for modification".
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Luca Cardelli has stated that OOP languages have "extremely poor modularity properties with respect to class extension and modification", and tend to be extremely complex.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Leo Brodie says that information hiding can lead to duplicate code, which goes against the don't repeat yourself rule of software development.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance can be supported via the class or the prototype, which have differences but use similar terms like object and instance.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In class-based programming, the most common type of OOP, an object is an instance of a class.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] The class defines the data (variables) and methods (logic).
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] An object is created via the constructor.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Every instance of the class has the same set of variables and methods.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Classes may inherit from other classes, creating a hierarchy of classes: a case of a subclass inheriting from a super-class.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, an `Employee` class might inherit from a `Person` class which endows the Employee object with the variables from `Person`.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] The subclass may add variables and methods that do not affect the super-class.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Most languages also allow the subclass to override super-class methods.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Some languages support multiple inheritance, where a class can inherit from more than one class, and other languages similarly support mixins or traits.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, a mixin called UnicodeConversionMixin might add a method unicode_to_ascii() to both a FileReader and a WebPageScraper class.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] An abstract class cannot be directly instantiated as an object.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Other classes are utility classes which contain only class variables and methods and are not meant to be instantiated or subclassed.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Instead of providing a class concept, in prototype-based programming, an object is linked to another object, called its *prototype* or *parent*.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In Self, an object may have multiple or no parents, but in the most popular prototype-based language, JavaScript, an object has exactly one prototype link, up to the base object whose prototype is null.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] A prototype acts as a model for new objects.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, if you have an object `fruit`, you can make two objects `apple` and `orange` that share traits of the `fruit` prototype.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Prototype-based languages also allow objects to have their own unique properties, so the `apple` object might have an attribute `sugar_content`, while the `orange` or `fruit` objects do not.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In all OOP languages, via object composition, an object can contain other objects.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, an `Employee` object might contain an `Address` object, along with other information like `name` and `position`.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Composition is a "has-a" relationships, like "an employee has an address".
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Some languages, like Go, don't support inheritance.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Instead, they encourage "composition over inheritance", where objects are built using smaller parts instead of parent-child relationships.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, instead of inheriting from class Person, the Employee class could simply contain a Person object.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] This lets the Employee class control how much of Person it exposes to other parts of the program.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Delegation is another language feature that can be used as an alternative to inheritance.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Programmers have different opinions on inheritance.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Bjarne Stroustrup, author of C++, has stated that it is possible to do OOP without inheritance.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Rob Pike has criticized inheritance for creating complex hierarchies instead of simpler solutions.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] People often think that if one class inherits from another, it means the subclass "is a" more specific version of the original class.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] This presumes the program semantics are that objects from the subclass can always replace objects from the original class without problems.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] This concept is known as behavioral subtyping, more specifically the Liskov substitution principle.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] However, this is often not true, especially in programming languages that allow mutable objects, objects that change after they are created.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In fact, subtype polymorphism as enforced by the type checker in OOP languages cannot guarantee behavioral subtyping in most if not all contexts.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, the circle-ellipse problem is notoriously difficult to handle using OOP's concept of inheritance.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Behavioral subtyping is undecidable in general, so it cannot be easily implemented by a compiler.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Because of this, programmers must carefully design class hierarchies to avoid mistakes that the programming language itself cannot catch.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] A method may be invoked via dynamic dispatch such that the method is selected at runtime instead of compile time.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] If the method choice depends on more than one type of object (such as other objects passed as parameters), it's called multiple dispatch.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In this context, a method call is also known as message passing, meaning the method name and its inputs are like a message sent to the object for it to act on.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Dynamic dispatch works together with inheritance: if an object doesn't have the requested method, it looks up to its parent class (delegation), and continues up the chain to find a matching method.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Polymorphism in OOP refers to subtyping or subtype polymorphism, where a function can work with a specific interface and thus manipulate entities of different classes in a uniform manner.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, imagine a program has two shapes: a circle and a square.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Both come from a common class called "Shape." Each shape has its own way of drawing itself.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] With subtype polymorphism, the program doesn't need to know the type of each shape, and can simply call the "Draw" method for each shape.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] The programming language runtime will ensure the correct version of the "Draw" method runs for each shape.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Because the details of each shape are handled inside their own classes, this makes the code simpler and more organized, enabling strong separation of concerns.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] An object's methods can access the object's data.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Many programming languages use a special word, like `this` or `self`, to refer to the current object.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In languages that support open recursion, a method in an object can call other methods in the same object, including itself, using this special word.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] This allows a method in one class to call another method defined later in a subclass, a feature known as late binding.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Design patterns are common solutions to problems in software design.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Some design patterns are especially useful for OOP, and design patterns are typically introduced in an OOP context.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Sometimes, objects represent real-world things and processes in digital form.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, a graphics program may have objects such as `circle`, `square`, and `menu`.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] An online shopping system might have objects such as `shopping cart`, `customer`, and `product`.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Niklaus Wirth said, "This paradigm [OOP] closely reflects the structure of systems in the real world and is therefore well suited to model complex systems with complex behavior".
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] However, more often, objects represent abstract entities, like an open file or a unit converter.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Not everyone agrees that OOP makes it easy to copy the real world exactly or that doing so is even necessary.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Bob Martin suggests that because classes are software, their relationships don't match the real-world relationships they represent.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Bertrand Meyer argues that a program is not a model of the world but a model of some part of the world; "Reality is a cousin twice removed".
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Steve Yegge noted that natural languages lack the OOP approach of naming a thing (object) before an action (method), as opposed to functional programming which does the reverse.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] This can make an OOP solution more complex than one written via procedural programming.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] The following are notable software design patterns for OOP objects.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] A common anti-pattern is the God object, an object that knows or does too much.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Both OOP and relational database management systems (RDBMSs) are widely used in software today.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] However, relational databases don't store objects directly, which creates a challenge when using them together.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] This issue is called object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] To solve this problem, developers use different methods, but none of them are perfect.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] One of the most common solutions is object-relational mapping (ORM), which helps connect object-oriented programs to relational databases.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Examples of ORM tools include Visual FoxPro, Java Data Objects, and Ruby on Rails ActiveRecord.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Some databases, called object databases, are designed to work with OOP.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] However, they have not been as popular or successful as relational databases.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Date and Darwen have proposed a theoretical foundation that uses OOP as a kind of customizable type system to support RDBMSs, but it forbids objects containing pointers to other objects.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In responsibility-driven design, classes are built around what they need to do and the information they share, in the form of a contract.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] This is different from data-driven design, where classes are built based on the data they need to store.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] According to Wirfs-Brock and Wilkerson, the originators of responsibility-driven design, responsibility-driven design is the better approach.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Researchers have tried to formally define the semantics of OOP.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance presents difficulties, particularly with the interactions between open recursion and encapsulated state.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Researchers have used recursive types and co-algebraic data types to incorporate essential features of OOP.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Abadi and Cardelli defined several extensions of System F<: that deal with mutable objects, allowing both subtype polymorphism and parametric polymorphism (generics), and were able to formally model many OOP concepts and constructs.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Although far from trivial, static analysis of object-oriented programming languages such as Java is a mature field, with several commercial tools.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Many popular programming languages, like C++, Java, and Python, use OOP.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] In the past, OOP was widely accepted, but recently, some programmers have criticized it and prefer functional programming instead.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] A study by Potok et al. found no major difference in productivity between OOP and procedural programming.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Some believe that OOP places too much focus on using objects rather than on algorithms and data structures.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, programmer Rob Pike pointed out that OOP can make programmers think more about type hierarchy than composition.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] He has called OOP "the Roman numerals of computing".
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Rich Hickey, creator of Clojure, described OOP as overly simplistic, especially when it comes to representing real-world things that change over time.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Alexander Stepanov said that OOP tries to fit everything into a single type, which can be limiting.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] He argued that sometimes we need multisorted algebras: families of interfaces that span multiple types, such as in generic programming.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Stepanov also said that calling everything an "object" doesn't add much understanding.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] OOP was created to make code easier to reuse and maintain.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] However, it was not designed to clearly show the flow of a program's instructions.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] As computers began using more parallel processing and multiple threads, it became more important to understand and control how instructions flow.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Paul Graham believes big companies like OOP because it helps manage large teams of average programmers.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] He argues that OOP adds structure, making it harder for one person to make serious mistakes, but at the same time restrains smart programmers.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Raymond, a Unix programmer and open-source software advocate, argues that OOP is not the best way to write programs.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Richard Feldman says that, while OOP features helped some languages stay organized, their popularity comes from other reasons.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Lawrence Krubner argues that OOP doesn't offer special advantages compared to other styles, like functional programming, and can complicate coding.
[src:eiffel-language/object-oriented-programming] Luca Cardelli says that OOP is slower and takes longer to compile than procedural programming.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] SCOOP defines a way for an object oriented program to be written without the concept of threads, locks, or other typical multiprogramming methods.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] This allows the compiler or runtime environment to optimize the amount of concurrency as well as eliminate typical design flaws such as deadlock.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] The model was first designed in the early 1990s and published in 1993 in the Communications of the ACM An updated version was described in chapter 30 of the book *Object-Oriented Software Construction*.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] A prototype implementation was developed in 1995 by Eiffel Software.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] An article by Compton and Walker provides an overview of SCOOP and describes another early implementation.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] Nienaltowski, Arslan and Meyer have published a description of the model as of 2003.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] Work on SCOOP proceeded at the Chair of Software Engineering at ETH Zurich.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] SCOOP became available as a standard part of EiffelStudio early in 2011.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] SCOOP works by allowing references to certain objects to be declared as **separate**.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] In the code below, an entity `local_inventory` is declared as a separate type, by specifying the Eiffel language keyword `separate` in the declaration.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] A separate object may be handled by a **SCOOP processor** that is different from the processor handling the referencing object.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] A SCOOP processor is the abstract notion of an autonomous thread of control that handles the execution of operations on one or more objects.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] SCOOP processors are independent of underlying concurrency mechanisms like processor threads, multiple processor cores, and distributed computer systems.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] In addition to the concept of separateness, SCOOP exploits the principles of *design by contract* as part of the SCOOP strategy for synchronizing access to shared separate resources.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] For example, a precondition for a consumer wishing to access an item in the inventory example above, might be that such an item does currently exist.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] This would be expressed with a contract on the feature of class `INVENTORY` which returns the item.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] In traditional, sequential processing, a client intending to call `local_inventory.item` would be responsible for making certain that the precondition `local_inventory.has_item` holds before making the call.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] If the call to `item` were made in a state in which `has_item` did not hold, the caller would incur a precondition violation exception.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] In the presence of SCOOP and given the separateness of `local_inventory`, making the check on `has_item` before calling `item` would not be reliable.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] This is because the state of `local_inventory` could have been changed by requests from other SCOOP processors between the time that the check was made and the time that `item` could be called.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] As a result, when SCOOP is enabled, the precondition `has_item` is transformed from a **correctness condition**, which will cause an exception in the case of a violation, to a **wait condition**.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] The wait condition will cause the execution of `item` to be delayed until such time as `has_item` holds.
[src:eiffel-language/scoop-software] In the Eiffel Software implementation, if SCOOP is not enabled, the `separate` keyword is ignored and sequential processing is assumed.
